SIMPLE: saki
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Saki
<hw>Sa"ki</hw> <pr>(s⟦amac⟧"k⟦icr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. &
Pg. <ets>saki</ets>; probably from the native name.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of South American
monkeys of the genus <gen>Pithecia</gen>. They have large ears, and a
long hairy tail which is not prehensile.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The black saki (<spn>Pithecia satanas</spn>), the
white-headed (<spn>Pithecia leucocephala</spn>), and the red-backed, or
hand-drinking, saki (<spn>Pithecia chiropotes</spn>), are among the
best-known.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Saki</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Saki
<hw>Sa"ki</hw> <pr>(s⟦aum⟧"k⟦esl⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The
alcoholic drink of Japan. It is made from rice; it is usually spelled
<asp>sake</asp>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sakiyeh</ent>⟦br⟧
